{"repo": "aerkalov/ebooklib", "pull_number": 353, "instance_id": "aerkalov__ebooklib-353", "issue_numbers": [336], "base_commit": "7058a9e577b3529f1a494b7166a8019ef4c556f4", "patch": "diff --git a/README.md b/README.md\nindex c4bcf46..ecb39c5 100644\n--- a/README.md\n+++ b/README.md\n@@ -112,6 +112,15 @@ book.add_item(epub.EpubNav())\n epub.write_epub(\"the_book_of_the_mysterious.epub\", book)\n ```\n \n+# Popular Projects using Ebooklib\n+1.  [Marker](https://github.com/VikParuchuri/marker)\n+2.  [ChatDev](https://github.com/OpenBMB/ChatDev)\n+3.  [DocsGPT](https://github.com/arc53/DocsGPT)\n+4.  [ebook2audiobook](https://github.com/DrewThomasson/ebook2audiobook)\n+5.  [SuperAGI](https://github.com/TransformerOptimus/SuperAGI)\n+6.  [bilingual_book_maker](https://github.com/yihong0618/bilingual_book_maker)\n+7.  [audiblz](https://github.com/santinic/audiblez)\n+\n \n # License\n EbookLib is licensed under the [AGPL license](LICENSE.txt).\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "Update list of software using ebooklib\nUpdate and maintaine a list of software using ebooklib.\n\nFull list should be here - https://github.com/aerkalov/ebooklib/wiki/Who-uses-ebooklib and README file should mention bigger projects.\n", "hints_text": "Hey @aerkalov , would like to take on this issue. \n\n", "all_hints_text": "Hey @aerkalov , would like to take on this issue. \n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/aerkalov/ebooklib/commit/5104bcc5eef322ee80d862a2dfb27fe53d9e35e5"], "created_at": "2025-11-03T09:48:10Z"}
{"repo": "aerkalov/ebooklib", "pull_number": 352, "instance_id": "aerkalov__ebooklib-352", "issue_numbers": [347], "base_commit": "7058a9e577b3529f1a494b7166a8019ef4c556f4", "patch": "diff --git a/ebooklib/epub.py b/ebooklib/epub.py\nindex 1c585c2..f543c8d 100644\n--- a/ebooklib/epub.py\n+++ b/ebooklib/epub.py\n@@ -77,15 +77,10 @@\n COVER_XML = six.b(\"\"\"<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?>\n <!DOCTYPE html>\n <html xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" xmlns:epub=\"http://www.idpf.org/2007/ops\" lang=\"en\" xml:lang=\"en\">\n- <head>\n-  <style>\n-    body { margin: 0em; padding: 0em; }\n-    img { max-width: 100%; max-height: 100%; }\n-  </style>\n- </head>\n- <body>\n-   <img src=\"\" alt=\"\" />\n- </body>\n+  <head></head>\n+  <body>\n+    <img src=\"\" alt=\"\" style=\"height:100%; text-align:center\" />\n+  </body>\n </html>\"\"\")\n \n \n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "Cover does not take full width/height on Kobo reader\nHello,\nOn my Kobo reader, the cover image of epubs generated with this library do not expand to full size. They take around 40% of the available width/height, both on miniature and on first page while reading, and stay in the top-left corner.\nThis happened first while using [lightnovel-crawler](https://github.com/dipu-bd/lightnovel-crawler/blob/master/lncrawl/binders/epub.py), then I tested the [cover example](https://github.com/aerkalov/ebooklib/tree/master/samples/02_cover_create) and got the same problem.\nThis problem does not happen on google play books, I didn't test other epub readers.\nIt looks like the `properties=\"cover-image\"`  has no influence on the cover image chosen for the miniature by Kobo readers. The miniature is just the first page, so the xhtml wrapper is shown instead of the jpg. Thus the miniature and the first page are a single issue.\n\nIt works fine (although not standard) when directly showing the jpg without the xhtml wrapper, but then epubcheck shows an error (opf043), stating that image/jpeg (I tried image/jpg as well) is not a standard mime type for spine items and no `fallback` attribute is provided. I tried adding the xhtml wrapper as [fallback](https://w3c.github.io/epub-specs/epub33/core/#attrdef-item-fallback) and it works perfectly on my reader, as well as when running epubcheck.\n\nSo I replaced this:\n```xml\n<manifest>\n    <item href=\"image.jpg\" id=\"cover-img\" media-type=\"image/jpeg\" properties=\"cover-image\"/>\n    <item href=\"cover.xhtml\" id=\"cover\" media-type=\"application/xhtml+xml\"/>\n    ...\n</manifest>\n```\nWith this:\n```xml\n<manifest>\n    <item href=\"image.jpg\" id=\"cover\" media-type=\"image/jpeg\" properties=\"cover-image\" fallback=\"cover-xhtml\" />\n    <item href=\"cover.xhtml\" id=\"cover-xhtml\" media-type=\"application/xhtml+xml\"/>\n    ...\n</manifest>\n```\nAnd it works fine. It would be great to integrate this in `set_cover()` to support kobo readers perfectly, although it's not urgent.\n\nI didn't manage to write an xhtml wrapper that takes full size, even by using 100vw and 100vh instead of 100% in CSS or by using an SVG, so the `fallback` attribute seems the easiest way to solve this.\n", "hints_text": "Fixed this in [GreenCake3/ebooklib](https://github.com/GreenCake3/ebooklib). However, this changes too many things.\nIt introduced 4 changes that may be problematic:\n- `cover` is now the default id for EpubCover, thus referencing `cover-img` directly in the spine or to retrieve the EpubCover will result in an error (`cover-img` should not be referenced in the spine anyway since images are not allowed in the spine according to epubcheck)\n- `cover-html` is now the default id for EpubCoverHtml, thus introducing another item with id `cover-html` will cause a conflict\n- Relying on id `cover` to get the EpubCoverHtml will return an EpubCover\n- Adding an EpubCover but not an EpubCoverHtml now raises a warning (maybe this is not necessary since `set_cover()` supports adding cover without html wrapper?)\n\nAnother option is to just add EpubCoverHtml as fallback of EpubCover, considering that it may be fixed on Kobo's side. This does not involve changing default ids and thus is much safer. It will allow users to directly reference `cover-img` instead of `cover` in the spine. However, it will not fix this issue for older scripts, just allow new users or maintained projects to choose to use `cover-img` directly to solve the problem. It will also simplify the API since the EPUB will still be valid when `cover-img` is used where `cover` is expected in the spine.\n\n@aerkalov I hope to get an answer as to whether I should implement the second option, make a PR for the first option, or just wait for it to be fixed on Kobo's side.\nLooking at the Kobo EPUB Guidlines seems like they don't expect property attribute at all. - https://github.com/kobolabs/epub-spec?tab=readme-ov-file#cover-images\n\nFor the CSS you can check Booktype version, probably should put that to be the default for ebooklib. That CSS used to work on most of devices couple of years back - https://github.com/booktype/Booktype/blob/master/lib/booktype/convert/epub/cover.py\n\nIn this file (cover.py) you can see we didn't use add_cover from ebooklib, we just manually inserted it. That is always an option. And when it comes to writing, there are always options for write_epub which could specify maybe that you don't want property attribute. As far as I recall the specification it was needed back then.\n\n\nTook another look at this issue and found a problem in [epub.py](https://github.com/aerkalov/ebooklib/blob/master/ebooklib/epub.py).\n\nIn `epub.py`, in `COVER_XML` (the template for the cover wrapper) there *is* a `<style>` in `<head>` that handles images, but in the processed cover.xhtml, it *doesn't* appear, thus the `<img>` has no custom CSS. It is because an `EpubCoverHtml` is rendered as an `EpubHtml` with `COVER_XML` as content, and, as the docs say about `EpubHtml`, \"It will ignore whatever you have in the `<head>` element\".\n\nThe easiest workaround would be to move `<style>` to `<body>`, but it's forbidden in XHTML. It looks like we have to introduce a private attribute `_keep_head` in `EpubHtml` that is set to True in `EpubCoverHtml.get_content()` before calling `super().get_content()`. Otherwise, if `<head>` was always kept, it would be a breaking change for apps that rely on this behavior, following the docs.\n\nI will make a PR about this in a few days. It doesn't need any change in the public API and it will allow to change `<style>` in `COVER_XML` to fix the current issue. This also removes an inconsistency: why add `<style>` to `COVER_XML` if it will be removed at rendering ? This could cause confusion.\nThe `style` attribute is deprecated in XHTML ([w3.org/TR/xhtml-basic](https://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml-basic/#:~:text=Style%20Attribute%20Module)) but it looks like EPUB 3.3's  [XHTML Content Documents](https://www.w3.org/TR/epub-33/#sec-xhtml-req) do not need to be valid XHTML documents as defined in XHTML basic: they only need to be HTML documents with an XML syntax and some other constraints.\n\nIt means that we can rely on the inline `style` HTML attribute to **avoid introducing `EpubHtml._keep_head`**. Using inline styles is generally discouraged but here it is the cleanest solution.\n\nBooktype's CSS indeed works on Kobo (I didn't test it on other platforms).\n\n", "all_hints_text": "Fixed this in [GreenCake3/ebooklib](https://github.com/GreenCake3/ebooklib). However, this changes too many things.\nIt introduced 4 changes that may be problematic:\n- `cover` is now the default id for EpubCover, thus referencing `cover-img` directly in the spine or to retrieve the EpubCover will result in an error (`cover-img` should not be referenced in the spine anyway since images are not allowed in the spine according to epubcheck)\n- `cover-html` is now the default id for EpubCoverHtml, thus introducing another item with id `cover-html` will cause a conflict\n- Relying on id `cover` to get the EpubCoverHtml will return an EpubCover\n- Adding an EpubCover but not an EpubCoverHtml now raises a warning (maybe this is not necessary since `set_cover()` supports adding cover without html wrapper?)\n\nAnother option is to just add EpubCoverHtml as fallback of EpubCover, considering that it may be fixed on Kobo's side. This does not involve changing default ids and thus is much safer. It will allow users to directly reference `cover-img` instead of `cover` in the spine. However, it will not fix this issue for older scripts, just allow new users or maintained projects to choose to use `cover-img` directly to solve the problem. It will also simplify the API since the EPUB will still be valid when `cover-img` is used where `cover` is expected in the spine.\n\n@aerkalov I hope to get an answer as to whether I should implement the second option, make a PR for the first option, or just wait for it to be fixed on Kobo's side.\nLooking at the Kobo EPUB Guidlines seems like they don't expect property attribute at all. - https://github.com/kobolabs/epub-spec?tab=readme-ov-file#cover-images\n\nFor the CSS you can check Booktype version, probably should put that to be the default for ebooklib. That CSS used to work on most of devices couple of years back - https://github.com/booktype/Booktype/blob/master/lib/booktype/convert/epub/cover.py\n\nIn this file (cover.py) you can see we didn't use add_cover from ebooklib, we just manually inserted it. That is always an option. And when it comes to writing, there are always options for write_epub which could specify maybe that you don't want property attribute. As far as I recall the specification it was needed back then.\n\n\nTook another look at this issue and found a problem in [epub.py](https://github.com/aerkalov/ebooklib/blob/master/ebooklib/epub.py).\n\nIn `epub.py`, in `COVER_XML` (the template for the cover wrapper) there *is* a `<style>` in `<head>` that handles images, but in the processed cover.xhtml, it *doesn't* appear, thus the `<img>` has no custom CSS. It is because an `EpubCoverHtml` is rendered as an `EpubHtml` with `COVER_XML` as content, and, as the docs say about `EpubHtml`, \"It will ignore whatever you have in the `<head>` element\".\n\nThe easiest workaround would be to move `<style>` to `<body>`, but it's forbidden in XHTML. It looks like we have to introduce a private attribute `_keep_head` in `EpubHtml` that is set to True in `EpubCoverHtml.get_content()` before calling `super().get_content()`. Otherwise, if `<head>` was always kept, it would be a breaking change for apps that rely on this behavior, following the docs.\n\nI will make a PR about this in a few days. It doesn't need any change in the public API and it will allow to change `<style>` in `COVER_XML` to fix the current issue. This also removes an inconsistency: why add `<style>` to `COVER_XML` if it will be removed at rendering ? This could cause confusion.\nThe `style` attribute is deprecated in XHTML ([w3.org/TR/xhtml-basic](https://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml-basic/#:~:text=Style%20Attribute%20Module)) but it looks like EPUB 3.3's  [XHTML Content Documents](https://www.w3.org/TR/epub-33/#sec-xhtml-req) do not need to be valid XHTML documents as defined in XHTML basic: they only need to be HTML documents with an XML syntax and some other constraints.\n\nIt means that we can rely on the inline `style` HTML attribute to **avoid introducing `EpubHtml._keep_head`**. Using inline styles is generally discouraged but here it is the cleanest solution.\n\nBooktype's CSS indeed works on Kobo (I didn't test it on other platforms).\nGreat find! Thanks for this. Such a lame bug, no woder people were complaining. One of the things which could be done (besider generating custom cover page) is something like this:\n\n```\n    cover_css = epub.EpubItem(uid=\"style_cover\", file_name=\"style/cover.css\", media_type=\"text/css\", content=\"\")\n    book.add_item(cover_css)\n\n    cover = book.get_item_with_id(\"cover\")\n    cover.add_item(cover_css)\n```\n\nThis way you attach CSS file to the cover page (as you would do with any other page) and <script> tag would show up in header. Should probably add this to the docs also.\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/aerkalov/ebooklib/commit/deef32eaffda20ac9333c1c731a8340942b7bf2c"], "created_at": "2025-10-30T15:54:14Z"}
